Preheat your #oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic{3%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a deep #saucepan(with a tight-fitting lid) on medium heat. Once hot, add half the @butter{} and allow to melt.

Add the onion, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and fry, stirring occasionally, until golden and soft, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, chop the @sweet potato{1}(chopped into 2cm chunks) into 2cm chunks (no need to peel).

Pop the sweet potato onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, once the onion has softened, add the @sugar{1/2%tsp} and half the garlic to the onion. Stir together and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir the @basmati rice{150%grams} into the onion and garlic until coated, ~{1%minute}.

Add 1/4 tsp @salt{1/4%tsp} and the @water{300%ml} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced chorizo{90%grams} and fry for ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the @tomato puree{30%grams}, @Cajun spice mix{1%sachet} and remaining garlic. Cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Add less Cajun spice mix if you'd prefer things milder.

Lower the heat to medium, then add the @water{100%ml} and @vegetable stock paste{15%grams}. Simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut the @lime{1}(cut into wedges) into wedges.

Once the sauce has thickened, stir the @peas{120%grams}, cooked rice, @honey{1%tbsp} and remaining @butter{} into the frying pan.

Add a good squeeze of lime juice and stir through the rice.

Once roasted, stir the sweet potato through the rice. Taste and season with @salt{}, @pepper{} and more lime juice if needed. Add a splash of @water{} if it's a little too dry.

When everything's ready, share the Cajun chorizo spiced rice between your #bowls{}.

Crumble over the @Greek style salad cheese{50%grams} and top with a drizzle of @soured cream{75%grams}.

Serve any remaining lime wedges alongside.

Enjoy!